Excessive restrictions on mobile number transfers are under scrutiny.
What about fees and points?
(Newswitch) - Yahoo! News
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications is starting full-scale studies to revise the Mobile Number Portability System (MNP), which allows users to use their old phone number as is when changing mobile phone carriers.
At a meeting of experts on the 21st, they announced a plan to revise the MNP guidelines established in 2004.
The specific points at issue are wide-ranging, including the nature of MNP fees and the pros and cons of holding back those who wish to transfer.
With opposition expected from telecommunications companies, all eyes are on whether the move will help promote healthy market competition.
Unlimited mobile phone switching is still far from being a reality for telecommunications companies When MNP was introduced in 2006, the user fee was 2,000 yen, but now it is 3,000 yen.
The MNP fee income for the three major mobile communications companies is estimated to be 15.9 billion yen annually.
On the 21st, the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications enumerated the current situation surrounding MNP at the ``Working Group (WG) on Verification of Competition Rules,&#39;&#39; a panel of experts that discusses the competitive environment of the telecommunications market.
They also criticized the opening hours for issuing MNP reservation numbers, which are required when consumers transfer to another carrier.
Major telecommunications companies accept applications online, but due to operational reasons for their core systems, most applications are accepted between 9:00 and 20:00.
The working group&#39;s materials clearly stated that the direction of future considerations would be to provide all-day support in principle.
It is also viewed as a problem that mobile carriers try to deter people who wish to transfer to MNP by giving them points.
This was based on the judgment that excessive restrictions could impede fair competition.
Partner Shunichi Kita of Nomura Research Institute, who serves as a member of the working group, said, ``We will ask users to give us time to explain the provision of economic benefits or obtain their permission, and we will promptly issue a number to users who do not consent and end the process.&#39;&#39; &quot;It is important to first thoroughly implement this process.&quot;
However, among the series of points at issue, regarding MNP fees, there is a structural problem: ``The higher the fees, the harder it is to lose customers, so it is difficult to motivate them to actively lower them.&#39;&#39; (Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications official) said.
If an operator emerges that takes the initiative to lower MNP fees, there are concerns that the number of customers leaving that company will increase and that corporate efforts will not be rewarded.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications has also pointed out that many countries overseas do not require users to pay fees for MNP, and there is a possibility that Japan will do the same.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications plans to compile the results of the working group into a report around September or October, and then begin procedures to revise the MNP guidelines.
If revisions are made, they are expected to take place after 2021.
Mobile carriers are likely to have to worry about issues such as sales and customer support.
